, Philip Freeman presents the most readable translation of the Poetics yet produced, making this indispensable handbook more accessible, engaging, and useful than ever before.In addition to its inviting and reliable translation, a commentary on each section, and the original Greek on facing pages, this edition of the Poetics features unique bullet points, chapter headings, and section numbers to help guide readers through Aristotle’s unmatched introduction to the art of writing and reading stories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAlcmaeon (mythology).  aAmanita.  aAncient Greek comedy.  aAuthor.  aBasic Story.  aCatharsis.  aCity Of.  aCleophon (politician).  aCoccidioides.  aComedy.  aCompost.  aCostume.  aCresphontes.  aCulture.  aDescription.  aDiscourses (Meher Baba).  aElegiac couplet.  aEucleides.  aEuripides.  aEurypylus.  aFeeling.  aFine art.  aFungus.  aFurniture.  aHaemon.  aHamartia.  aHerodotus.  aHeterobasidion annosum.  aIambic trimeter.  aIllyrians.  aIndigenous peoples.  aInner ear.  aIntarsia.  aIphigenia.  aLysistrata.  aMarquetry.  aMegara.  aMetaphor.  aMisery (novel).  aModern language.  aMycelium.  aMycenae.  aNarration.  aNarrative.  aNeoptolemus.  aNeosartorya.  aOdysseus.  aOdyssey.  aOrganism.  aOviparity.  aPeleus.  aPeripeteia.  aPhiloctetes (Sophocles play).  aPhylum.  aPity.  aPlaywright.  aPlot device.  aPoetics (Aristotle).  aPoetry.  aPost hoc ergo propter hoc.  aPreposition and postposition.  aProse.  aProtagonist.  aRecitation.  aRhapsode.  aRoutledge.  aRussula.  aS. (Dorst novel).  aSextus Empiricus.  aSinon.  aSocratic dialogue.  aSophocles.  aSophron.  aSpecial effect.  